","French:","variant of <b>Bourgouin</b> (and, in North America, an altered form of this), a habitational name for someone from Burgundy (Old French <i>Bourgogne</i>), a region of eastern France having Dijon as its center. The area was invaded by the <i>Burgundii</i>, an ancient Germanic tribe from whom it takes its name, in about  AD  480. The duchy of Burgundy, created in 877 by Charles II, King of the Western Franks, was extremely powerful in the later Middle Ages, especially under Philip the Bold (1342–1404; duke from 1363). Compare   Bourgoyne   and   Bourguignon  ."]}]},{"name":"Barthelmew","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: from an altered form of the personal name <i>Bartholomaeus</i> (see   Bartholomew  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Barthelmess","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt.","German: variant of   Barthelmes  . Compare   Bartmess  ."]},{"name":"Bartimus","meanings":["Americanized form of German   Barthelmes   or of some other similar (like-sounding) surname."]},{"name":"Bartholomew","meanings":["Of New Testament origin, the name of an apostle mentioned in all the synoptic gospels (Matthew, Mark, and Luke) and in the Acts of the Apostles. It is an Aramaic formation meaning ‘son of Talmai’, and has been assumed by many scholars to be a byname of the apostle   Nathaniel .  <i>Talmai</i> is a Hebrew name, said to mean ‘abounding in furrows’ (Numbers 13:22)."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Barthelmew Bourgoyne was born about 1297, in Cambridgeshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Barthelmew Bourgoyne, was 28 and his mother, Elizabeth De Vere, was 23. He married Mrs. Barthelmew Burgoyne in 1327, in Cambridge, Cambridgeshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1332, in England, United Kingdom, at the age of 36."},"et":{"about 1297–1332":"umbes 1297–1332","1297–1332":"1297–1332","1296–Female":"1296–Surnud","1329–1364":"13